Take the dimensional incompressible Navier–Stokes equation  

\[
\rho\bigl(\partial_t\mathbf u+\mathbf u\!\cdot\!\nabla\mathbf u\bigr)
   =-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^{2}\mathbf u+\mathbf f .
\]

Introduce one speed \(U\) and one length \(L\), and set  

\[
\hat{\mathbf x}=\frac{\mathbf x}{L},\;\;
\hat t=\frac{U t}{L},\;\;
\hat{\mathbf u}=\frac{\mathbf u}{U},\;\;
\hat p=\frac{p}{\rho U^{2}} .
\]

Rewrite every derivative with \(\hat{}\) variables and divide by \(\rho U^{2}/L\); the result is  

\[
\boxed{\;
\partial_{\hat t}\hat{\mathbf u}+\hat{\mathbf u}\!\cdot\!\hat{\nabla}\hat{\mathbf u}
   =-\hat{\nabla}\hat p+\frac{1}{Re}\,\hat{\nabla}^{2}\hat{\mathbf u}
   +\frac{L}{\rho U^{2}}\mathbf f\;}
\qquad
\text{with } Re=\frac{\rho U L}{\mu}.
\]

Thus **Reynolds number appears as the single dimension-less factor \(1/Re\) in front of the viscous term**, signalling how strongly viscosity counteracts the inertially driven motion. Setting \(Re\to\infty\) recovers the inviscid (Euler) limit; setting \(Re\ll1\) gives the Stokes flow regime.
